## 7.17 Source position metadata

Every form the reader produces carries a `:pos` metadata field. The field contains file, line, column.

```scheme
(let ((forms (parse \"(+ 1 2)\" :filename \"repl\")))
  (form-pos (car forms)))
;; => (:filename \"repl\" :line 1 :column 1)
```

The position travels with the form through macro expansion and into evaluation. When an error is raised at eval time, the error record's `:location` field is derived from the form's position. This is how Motoi's error messages know where in your source the problem happened.

## 7.18 The reader and macros

The reader produces forms. The macro expander consumes forms. Together they are a pipeline:

```
source string
  → reader
  → list of forms
  → macro expander
  → list of expanded forms
  → interpreter
  → result
```

Each stage is introspectable. The reader is exposed via `parse`. The expander is exposed via `macroexpand`. The interpreter is exposed via `eval`. You can call any one of them directly and see its output.

This modularity is why introspection works. Every stage has a public verb. Every stage produces data. Every stage's output can be fed to the next stage manually.

## 7.19 A worked example — the round-trip

Parse a string. Expand the resulting form. Evaluate the expansion.

```scheme
(define src \"(when (> x 0) (display x))\")
(define forms (parse src))
(define expanded (map macroexpand forms))
(define results (map eval expanded))
```

Four lines. Each one is a stage of the pipeline. Each one produces data you can inspect.

Now if any stage produces something unexpected, you know exactly where. `forms` wrong → reader bug or your source is malformed. `expanded` wrong → macro bug. `results` wrong → runtime bug.

This bisection is what introspection at every stage buys you.

