## 7.22 A working idiom

When you need to programmatically construct code and evaluate it, use the reader:

```scheme
(define (eval-string src)
  (let ((forms (parse src))
        (result nil))
    (for-each
      (lambda (f)
        (set! result (eval (macroexpand f))))
      forms)
    result))
```

Now `(eval-string \"(+ 1 2)\")` returns 3. You have a small eval-a-string verb built from the pipeline primitives.

This is how you would build a REPL from scratch — that is Appendix C's territory, briefly. The primitives are all here in Chapter 7 and Chapter 6.

## 7.23 Closing seed

The reader is the layer everyone forgets exists. It is silent, deterministic, and always there. When it does its job, no one thinks about it. When it does not — when a source position is wrong, a comment is dropped, a numeric literal is parsed as a symbol — introspection is the fastest route to diagnosis.

Wave 2 will unpack all of this. The seed lands the core verb and the pipeline picture.

Turn the page. Chapter 8 opens errors as data.

## 7.24 Deep-seed — reading from a file

The reader takes strings, not files. To read from a file you compose the file reader with the parse verb:

```scheme
(define (parse-file path)
  (parse (read-file path) :filename path))
```

Now `(parse-file \"my-cart.slat\")` returns the list of forms in the file. The `:filename` option lets the reader tag each form's position with the file path — essential for error messages that need to point at the source.

For a cart file that fails to load, this is your debugging tool. Parse the file. Walk the forms. Introspect each one. The reader will refuse to parse malformed source, so a successful parse means the syntax is at least valid; any downstream errors are semantic, not syntactic.

## 7.25 Deep-seed — source position introspection

Every form the reader produces has a `:pos` field. You can read it with `form-pos`:

```scheme
(let* ((forms (parse \"(+ 1\\n   2)\" :filename \"repl\"))
       (form (car forms)))
  (form-pos form))
;; => (:filename \"repl\" :line 1 :column 1 :end-line 2 :end-column 5)
```

The position spans the whole form — from the opening paren to the closing paren. Sub-forms have their own positions:

```scheme
(let* ((forms (parse \"(+ 1 2)\"))
       (form (car forms))
       (plus (car form))
       (one (cadr form)))
  (list (form-pos plus) (form-pos one)))
;; => ((:line 1 :column 2 :end-column 3)
;;     (:line 1 :column 4 :end-column 5))
```

Every atom carries its position. This is what error messages use to underline the offending token in your source.

## 7.26 Deep-seed — the reader and comments

Comments in Scheme start with `;`. The reader typically discards them. Motoi's reader can optionally preserve them as metadata on adjacent forms:

```scheme
(parse \"; a comment\\n(+ 1 2)\" :preserve-comments #t)
;; => ((+ 1 2))    ;; the form
;; with metadata: (:leading-comments (\"; a comment\") ...)
```

Preserving comments matters for tools that render source (documentation generators, formatters, IDE hover popups). The reader has the machinery; whether it is used depends on the option.

For debug introspection, comment preservation is usually off. For source-rendering tools, it is usually on. Motoi's reader supports both.

## 7.27 Turn the page

That is the seed. Chapter 8 opens errors as data. Turn the page.

## 7.28 Deep-seed — the pipeline revisited

The full source-to-result pipeline in Motoi is:

1. **Read**: source string → forms (with position metadata)
2. **Expand**: forms → expanded forms (macros unfolded)
3. **Evaluate**: expanded forms → results (in an environment)

Each stage is a public verb. Each stage returns data. Each stage can be introspected.

Chapters 5, 6, and 7 covered the three stages from the inside out. Chapter 5 was the environment layer that evaluation happens in. Chapter 6 was the macro expander. Chapter 7 was the reader.

Together, these three chapters let you see every layer of what happens when you type an expression at the REPL and hit enter. Nothing is hidden. Every stage is a verb call away.

## 7.29 A worked full pipeline

```scheme
(define src \"(when (> x 0) (display x))\")

;; Stage 1: read
(define forms (parse src))
;; => ((when (> x 0) (display x)))

;; Stage 2: expand
(define expanded (map macroexpand forms))
;; => ((if (> x 0) (begin (display x))))

;; Stage 3: evaluate (with x bound)
(define x 5)
(map eval expanded)
;; => (5)   ;; the display side-effect printed 5, returned void
```

Three verbs. Three stages. Every stage produces data. Nothing hidden.

This is what makes Motoi debuggable at the language level. You do not need a debugger. You have the stages.

## 7.30 Really turn the page

Chapter 8 opens errors as data. Every error is a record. Every record is introspectable. Every field has meaning. Turn the page.

## 7.31 A last practical note

The reader is Motoi's front door. Everything that enters the language passes through it. Every character you type at the REPL, every file you load, every string you evaluate — the reader is the first thing that touches it.

Because the reader is exposed as a verb, you can do everything the runtime does. You can build your own REPL variant. You can build a preprocessor. You can build a linter that parses your source and walks the forms without ever evaluating anything.

Wave 2 will walk these use cases. The seed lands the ground truth: parse is a verb, forms are data, positions are metadata, and the pipeline is visible from any prompt.

Turn the page. Chapter 8 opens errors as first-class data records that any introspection verb can read, filter, and interpret without any special exception-handling machinery. Errors are values, and values are introspectable, and Chapter 8 shows you every field on an error record and how to compose them with the LLM-augmented fix and pretty-error verbs that Chapter 13 will introduce more fully as part of the peer-verb family that turns cryptic errors into readable prose explanations you can act on right away without a trip through a stack trace.
